value.value: The cremasteric artery (external spermatic artery) is a branch of the Inferior epigastric artery which accompanies the spermatic cord, and supplies the Cremaster and other coverings of the cord, anastomosing with the testicular artery (internal spermatic artery in older texts). (In the female, the cremesteric artery is very small and accompanies the round ligament.).
The portion of the gubernacular bulb that is located within the abdomen.
The portion of the gubernacular bulb that is located external to the abdomen.
An embryonic or larval epithelium that is committed to form part of the nervous system.
An epithelium that is undergoing proliferation to provide large numbers of neuronal cells.
A neuroepithelium some of whose cells are undergoing terminal differentiation to become neuronal cells.
The layer of the developing cerebral cortex that is formed from the first cohort of neurons to migrate out of the cortical ventricular zone; split by the second wave into marginal zone and subplate.
Fibrocartilage containing bundles of yellow elastic fibers but with little or no white fibrous tissue.

Any of the cranial nerves, or their central nervous system analogs (the optic tract, the epiphyseal tract). These analogs are not true nerves, and are instead evaginated sensory afferents emanating from the brain.
A cranial nerve fiber tract that innervates the parietal eye.

definition.value: This should be classified as an evaginated sensory afferents rather than cranial nerves, as they are part of the CNS[ISBN:0471888893]

value.value: A cranial nerve fiber tract that innervates the pineal body.

definition.value: This should be classified as an evaginated sensory afferents rather than cranial nerves, as they are part of the CNS[ISBN:0471888893]

value.value: The more rostral of the two branches of the epiphyseal tract.
A taste bud that is located external to the digestive tube, on the head or body, as found in species such as goldfish.
A taste bud that is located on a barbel.
A taste bud that is located on a lip.
A taste bud that is located on the skin of the head.
A taste bud that is located in the pharynx.
A taste bud that is located on the roof of the mouth.
A taste bud that is located on a fin.
A taste bud that is located in the esophagus.

The pharyngeal nerve (pterygopalatine nerve) is a small branch arising from the posterior part of the pterygopalatine ganglion. It passes through the pharyngeal canal with the pharyngeal branch of the maxillary artery, and is distributed to the mucous membrane of the nasal part of the pharynx, behind the auditory tube.
A taste bud that is located on the skin of the trunk.
The artery of bulb of vestibule is a branch of the internal pudendal artery.

The autonomic nerve is a small nerve which carries postganglionic sympathetic and parasympathetic neurons from the zygomaticotemporal nerve; a branch of the maxillary nerve, to the lacrimal nerve; a branch of the ophthalmic nerve. These neurons derive from the superior cervical ganglion and the pterygopalatine ganglion respectively. They will travel to the lacrimal gland via the lacrimal nerve. Parasympathetic will induce lacrimation and vice versa.

label.value: olfactory tract linking bulb to ipsilateral dorsal telencephalon

value.value: The medial olfactory stria turns medialward behind the parolfactory area and ends in the subcallosal gyrus; in some cases a small intermediate stria is seen running backward to the anterior perforated substance.

A gland in the glandular region of the oviduct that secretes albumen over the ovum. In birds there are two regions of the oviduct, the first secretes a thin chalaziferous albumen layer, the second secretes a thicker albumen layer.
Any ligament that connects the coracoid process with the clavicle.

The inferior longitudinal fasciculus connects the temporal lobe and occipital lobe, running along the lateral walls of the inferior and posterior cornua of the lateral ventricle. The existence of this fasciculus independent from the occipitotemporal fasciculus has been questioned for the human being, such that it has been proposed that the term inferior longitudinal fasciculus be replaced by the term 'occipitotemporal projection'.
Part of cortex considered to function in higher level visual functions.
The part of the auditory cortex that is located on the superior temporal gyrus in the temporal lobe and receives point-to-point input from the ventral division of the medial geniculate complex.
The part of the auditory cortex that receive more diffuse input from the belt areas of the medial geniculate complex.

The occipitofrontal fasciculus passes backward from the frontal lobe, along the lateral border of the caudate nucleus, and on the medial aspect of the corona radiata; its fibers radiate in a fan-like manner and pass into the occipital and temporal lobes lateral to the posterior and inferior cornua.
Any sweat gland that is part of an areola.
Any commissure within the hindbrain.
